&#8217;s Best Pregnancy Looks<\/h4>\n      <\/a>\n    <\/article>\n    <article class=\"related-article\">\n      <a class=\"article-thumbnail-wrap\" href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3645699\/the-1919-theory-that-explains-why-police-officers-need-their-guns\/\" data-event=\"article-divider\">\n        <img class=\"article-thumbnail\" src=\"https:\/\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/12\/police-line.jpeg?w=100&amp;h=100&amp;crop=1\" alt=\"{short_title}}\">\n      <\/a>\n      <section class=\"tags\">\n        <a class=\"section-tag\" href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/history\/\" data-event=\"article-divider\">History<\/a>\n      <\/section>\n      <a class=\"article-title-link\" href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3645699\/the-1919-theory-that-explains-why-police-officers-need-their-guns\/\"  data-event=\"article-divider\">\n        <h4 class=\"article-title\">The 1919 Theory That Explains Why Police Officers Need Their Guns<\/h4>\n      <\/a>\n    <\/article>\n <\/div>\n\n<\/section>"],"single_article":{"url":"http:\/\/time.com\/3535728\/ebola-subway-bowling-balls-explainer\/","shortlink":"http:\/\/ti.me\/1D4oatO","title":"Can You Get Ebola From Subway Poles and Bowling Balls?","friendly_title":"Can You Get Ebola From Subway Poles and Bowling Balls?","post_type":"post","available":true,"time_article":true,"comments_allowed":true,"short_title":"Can You Get Ebola From Subway Poles and Bowling Balls?","excerpt":"Lots and lots of research says no","format":"brief","time":{"pretty":"Oct. 23, 2014","published":"2014-10-23 23:26:52","updated":"2014-10-24 03:26:52","minute":"11:26 pm","short":"10\/23"},"authors":[{"id":207020909,"url":"http:\/\/time.com\/author\/alexandra-sifferlin\/","name":"Alexandra Sifferlin","bio":"Alexandra Sifferlin is a writer for TIME. She covers public health issues including infectious and chronic disease, big ideas in medicine, and breaking news.","short_bio":"","types":[],"twitter":"acsifferlin","twitter_url":"https:\/\/twitter.com\/acsifferlin","gplus":"110376986433078721859","fb":"","email":"","thumbnail":"http:\/\/i1.wp.com\/timedotcom.files.wordpress.com\/2014\/01\/mg_1589.jpg?crop=441px%2C168px%2C2423px%2C2422px&resize=100%2C100","contributor":false,"search_link":false}],"content":"<aside class=\"right-rail-module rr-outbrain\" data-name=\"rr-outbrain\"><div class=\"OUTBRAIN\" data-src=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3535728\/ebola-subway-bowling-balls-explainer\/\" data-widget-id=\"SB_2\" data-ob-template=\"timemag\"><\/div><\/aside><p>Concerns were raised Thursday that the New York City doctor Craig Spencer, MD, who has been diagnosed with Ebola, had been to a Brooklyn bowling alley, had ridden the subway, and been inside an Uber taxi.<\/p>\n<p>So, can you get Ebola from bowling balls or subway poles, or Uber doorhandles for that matter?<\/p>\n<p>The short&mdash;and accurate&mdash;answer is no, and that&#8217;s based on what scientists know after decades of studying Ebola. Spencer was not symptomatic at the time, according to reports, which means he was not contagious at the time.<\/p>\n<p>But, you may ask again, shouldn&#8217;t people who rode on the same train, in the same taxi or who touched the same bowling balls as Spencer, worry a little?<\/p>\n<p>The research that exists says, again, no. The virus only survives inside bodily fluid of an infected person&mdash;meaning their blood, sweat, vomit or feces&mdash;that then comes into contact with an open sore or the mucus membranes of another person.<\/p>\n<p>Data suggests the virus can, in theory, survive on surfaces if it&#8217;s inside a liquid. But the only confirmed case of a person getting Ebola from an object or material that can carry infection was during an Ebola outbreak more than a decade ago in Gulu, Uganda, when a patient got the disease by sleeping with a blanket that had been used by an Ebola patient. Based on what we know about transmission of the virus, that blanket must have had an infected person&#8217;s wet bodily fluids on it.<\/p>\n<p>A study from 2007 by researchers at the Tulane School of Public Health and Tropical Medicine sampled 31 objects and surfaces that were not visibly bloody&mdash;they looked at bed frames, stethoscopes, etc&mdash;inside an isolation ward that treated Ebola patients. All specimens tested negative for the virus, suggesting the risk of transmission from surfaces was extremely low.<\/p>\n<p><em>Read next: <a href=\"http:\/\/time.com\/3535680\/how-ready-is-new-york-city-for-ebola\/?xid=time_readnext\" target=\"_blank\">How Ready Is New York City for Ebola?<\/a><\/em><\/p><aside class=\"right-rail-module rr-ad\" data-name=\"rr-ad\"><div class=\"right-rail-ad\" id=\"right-rail-ad-3535728\"><\/div><\/aside><aside class=\"right-rail-module rr-share\" data-name=\"rr-share\"><span class=\"social-links\">\n    <a class=\"time-icons time-icons-mail social-link-mail\" href=\"mailto:?subject=Can%20You%20Get%20Ebola%20From%20Subway%20Poles%20and%20Bowling%20Balls%3F%20%7C%20TIME&body=Can%20You%20Get%20Ebola%20From%20Subway%20Poles%20and%20Bowling%20Balls%3F%0A%0ALots%20and%20lots%20of%20research%20says%20no%0A%0Ahttp%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3535728%2Febola-subway-bowling-balls-explainer%2F\" data-event=\"email\" title=\"Click to Email this article\"><\/a>\n    <a class=\"time-icons time-icons-fb social-link-fb popup\" href=\"https:\/\/www.facebook.com\/sharer\/sharer.php?u=http%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3535728%2Febola-subway-bowling-balls-explainer%2F\" data-event=\"fb-share\" title=\"Click to post this article to Facebook\"><\/a>\n    <a class=\"time-icons time-icons-tw social-link-tw popup\" href=\"#\" data-href=\"https:\/\/twitter.com\/intent\/tweet?url=http%3A%2F%2Fti.me%2F1D4oatO&text=No%2C%20you%20can%27t%20get%20Ebola%20from%20the%20subway&via=TIMEHealth\" data-event=\"tweet\" title=\"Click to Tweet this article\"><\/a>\n    <a class=\"time-icons time-icons-linkedin social-link-linkedin popup\" href=\"http:\/\/www.linkedin.com\/shareArticle?mini=true&url=http%3A%2F%2Ftime.com%2F3535728%2Febola-subway-bowling-b